Cleric of Rodcet Nife, 26 Secrets revealed.<br> "My God... Its full of stars..."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uellywig.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ellywig</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 956<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/5/02 1:26:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=587.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What changes</span><hr size=1> Tattoing had very definite social class connotations for a very long time here in the US (and presumably in Europe). It was introduced to the populace at large by sailors who had visited Polynesia, and it had the class connotation to go with it. Sailors and those who associated with them (petty criminals, prostitutes, transients, etc.) wore tattoos, other folks didn't.<br>
<br>
The majority of society grew up under some variant of that lingering impression - in my grandfather's day, the ONLY societally-acceptable reason for having a tattoo was service in the Navy. Anything else would get you shunned in his whitebread midwestern small town.<br>
<br>
Body alteration is a facet of the youth culture, primarily -- and is judged that way. While there are some people who tattoo/pierce/ritually scar to get in touch with their cultural roots, many who do it are perceived as doing it to rebel against society. I mean, how many 4th-generation American mutts of mixed European ancestry are really getting in touch with their heritage with tattoos??? And rebellion comes at a price... until you are in the position to run things.<br>
<br>
I've had this debate with my sister-in-law... she doesn't understand why a few tattoos and piercings are killing her promotion chances at staid, solid, boring corporate office. She just doesn't understand that her boss isn't gonna put her in face-to-face contact with rich old lady clients, and she's gonna stay back in the cubicle farm on the phone, as long as she insists on publicly marching to the beat of her own drummer. No, life isn't fair. It just is that way.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Ellywig</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Cyncial and tattooless. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/udamienlogos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Damien Logos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/5/02 2:49:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=587.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://razza.org/ephestione/Download/Pictures/Fantasy/WomenandBeasts/images/strahd.jpg width=93 height=146></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What changes</span><hr size=1> My perception changes only in this:  In my eyes I see a person who placed no value in the natural beauty of their skin.  I have always loved the soft, clean, gentle look and feel of a woman's skin.  If she chooses to mar that skin, I actually feel I would not find myself as attracted to her body as I would otherwise.  I grew up with peers who would say &quot;Woah, I want a tattoo!&quot;, but I have never seen the attraction.<br>
<br>
After contemplating a bit, I think I've found my reasoning better.  I love the woman, all of her.  The tattoo is not her, the tattoo covers her, and takes away a part of her. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/udiamondtiger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DiamondTiger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/5/02 2:49:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=587.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What changes</span><hr size=1> That's very true Ellywig. My grandma nearly had a coronary when she found out I had a tattoo. She still loves me though. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I've worked at places where tattoos were strictly forbidden in the dress code. Not that any of my co-workers ever saw it. My tattoo is high up on my arm, and is easily covered by short sleeves. I can be rebellious when I wanna be, and not when the boss is looking. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I am labled rebellious by some folks, and it really doesn't bother me. <br>
<br>
I see the 'getting in touch with your heritage' as a search for identity. We mixed breeds don't have the linear heritage most people in the world do, as I see it. Body alteration is a way of claiming some part of your heratage as your own identity.  <p>Quianna Starthunder, Followers of the Stars<br>
Cleric of Rodcet Nife, 26 Secrets revealed.<br> "My God... Its full of stars..."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukrazakthule.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Krazak Thule</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 314<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/5/02 3:03:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=587.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Perception</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
I'm still the same person the person was talking to a few seconds ago, but *gasp* I have a purple oriental dragon on my upper arm! I must be a masochist! Or some kind of wierdo. Why, yes, I am wierd thank you. Does it hurt to be normal? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ah, but you see, your tatoos are part of what make you, YOU. <br>
<br>
At the point of discovery, you are no longer the &quot;same person&quot; you were a minute ago. You are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> different</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> now because more of you has been revealed to the person across from you. <br>
<br>
This is no different than talking to someone on the internet, who you've never met. You *think* you know them, and then finally you meet them in person. When you do, you find out they are like a 400 lb. hippo, and maybe that offends you. <br>
<br>
You see, everything about us, from our looks, to our religous beliefs, political beliefs, morals, drug use history, sexual preferences, favorite colors, and wether we like cats or dogs - all of this is *part* of what makes us who we are. <br>
<br>
<br>
Whenever you reveal something about yourself, you are creating a clearer picture of yourself for the other person. <br>
<br>
Some things you reveal, the other person may agree with. Some things, they won't. <br>
<br>
For instance, I could meet a beautiful woman, who was a brunette (my favorite), smart, liked football, music, and cats. All of these things I would find personally agreeable with. I would very much like this person. I could fall in love with this person.<br>
<br>
But if I found out she was a smoker... I'd realize right then, that she and I could never be romatically involved. <br>
<br>
It's not that the whole puzzle of the person is disagreeable with me. But an important part would be. <br>
<br>
<br>
The key thing to remember is, whenever you reveal something about yourself, you *change*. Maybe you think you stay the same (and to you, you will, because you know everything about yourself), but you change to everyone else who didn't know that information. <br>
<br>
-Krazak<br>
