<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
You are weak willed, or you aren't. From your point of view.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't see things in absolutes. Maybe that wasn't made clear in my post. <br>
<br>
There are few things in life that are absolute. There are shades of grey everywhere. Some people have strong willpower. Some people have none. Some people are somewhere in between. I admit my fault, but I am correcting it. So does that mean I have no willpower at all? No, it just means that at one point in my life, I was very weak willed. Now, I am stronger. This is life - the chance to change, to grow, to become stronger. To correct our weaknesses. <br>
<br>
I don't believe in evolution of man from monkeys, but I do believe each person can evolve from who they are when they are born. We don't *have* to be the same person all our lives. We can evolve. We can change. We do. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Don't say to me that I am weak willed because I have a smoke once a week...then turn around and say &quot;well, I'm different because I this that and the other thing&quot;.....<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't know if we're different, or not. I can only guess. <br>
<br>
I know one thing: you smoke, and I am fat. We both have work to do in the willpower department. But I am working on it, trying to evolve, trying to become stronger, trying to fix the things in my life that are bad or wrong. <br>
<br>
Are you?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Obviously your views are totally biased.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Biased about what? The smoking is bad? It is. There's no bias in that. It's just a fact. <br>
<br>
Biased that people who can't quit have less willpower than other people who can? What woud you call it then? Guts? Strength? It's something. <br>
<br>
If a person *knows* that smoking is bad, but doesn't quit, why is that? Willpower has to factor into that equation at some point in time. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There are people who have quit, if you don't realize that, well....back to the cave, I guess.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So, you would like to personally attack me then? Inferring that I am a &quot;cave man&quot;? What purpose does that serve?<br>
<br>
As for people who have quit - yes, I have known some. My own father quit smoking when he was very young, before he had me. I've known other people who have quit as well. My 8th grade science teacher quit smoking after 9 years of the habit. I will always remember his story. He had been some years quit when I met him, and he recalled how even then, some 8 years after having quit, his body was still puking up green matter. His lungs were still cleaning out the damage he had done to them. But like he said, &quot;the sooner you quit, the better chance you have for your body to repair itself&quot;. He didn't like hacking up green stuff in the morning, on occassions, but it beat the alternative - dying from cancer. <br>
<br>
And that is a great thing, that people can quit! Good for them. It means that for some people, there is hope. <br>
<br>
But here are the facts: A person who smokes is less likely to quit, the longer they continue to smoke. This is because of the addictive nature of nicotine. The more you smoke, the smaller your chances of quitting become. <br>
<br>
This is why, when I meet someone who smokes, it is very important for me to know how long they have been smoking. Because if it's been a long time, they aren't likely to quit. But if it's been a short time, perhaps they have a chance to quit. Maybe I can help them? <br>
<br>
Just because I draw certain conclusions about people, doesn't mean I'm a heartless person. I draw those conclusions, often times, to determine what *I* can do to be a part of the solution. <br>
<br>
I've tried to help my mom for years. But she is past the point of no return. She's tried to quit so many times... but the end result is the same: she cannot. The addiction has surpassed her own personal level of willpower. It is sad to see someone reach that point. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
And I never said smoking wasn't bad. I know first hand it is. Just like you.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Then my next question would be - do you ever intend to quit? If so, when?<br>
<br>
Also, why would you continue to smoke, to participate in an action that damages your body? Do you not respect your body? Do you not like it? <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
I was going more for the judging a book by it's cover...I guess since I'm of Irish lineage you assume I'm an alcoholic, too. And a violent drunk at that.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Once again, this is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> you</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> drawing these conclusions, not me. Please don't draw conclusions and then assume that I draw the same. <br>
<br>
We each draw our own conclusions, and make our own judgements. If you are Irish, the only thing I would assume about you is that you have a killer accent, and might sound something like Dolores Mary O'Riordan. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
And I didn't try to skirt any responsibility for my actions. But for real. I like tattoos. I came up with a nice design. It now resides on my body. Why? Becasue I like tats and the design. Point, set, match. Nothing else there. Saying something Just Is is saying something Just Is. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
